                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.512/3495: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morrow</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-03T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 3, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>356. Reference undated telegram received today from Consul at Nogales regarding
                    taxes. Please request that appropriate authorities in Sonora be instructed by
                    telegraph not to insist upon payment of taxes which have already been paid by
                    American citizens to persons exercising <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi>
                    authority and reiterate the statement contained in last paragraph of
                    Department’s 217, March 29, 6 p.m.</p>
                <p>Consul is being telegraphically informed of foregoing and instructed to advise
                    American citizens who may be forced to repay such taxes to Federal authorities
                    not to pay except under protest and to demand receipts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
